<Base title="LiT · Xiaochuan Li">
  <article class="prose">
    <div class="text-xs uppercase tracking-wider text-[var(--color-text-dim)] font-medium mb-2">
      Team project · May–Dec 2026 · DFKI / UTN
    </div>
    <h1>LiT — latent control states under prompt framing</h1>
    <p class="text-[var(--color-text-muted)] italic !text-lg !mb-8">
      Mechanistic interpretability of prompt-induced behavioral shifts.
    </p>

    <p>
      <em>Detail page coming.</em> Five-person collaboration supervised by Simon Ostermann (DFKI)
      with Michael Roth (UTN) as primary contact. Methods: probing, sparse autoencoders, activation
      patching, steering. I lead Objectives 3 and 4 — experimental design and downstream causal
      analysis.
    </p>

    <p>
      The core question is whether prompt framing–induced changes in model behavior correspond to
      causally relevant states in activation space, or merely to surface features that travel with
      the prompt. The methodological complement to <a href="/research/isotrace">Isotrace</a>:
      behavioral tracing and mech interp asking the same question from opposite ends.
    </p>
  </article>
</Base>
